<div id="review_2711286642" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2711286642" />
    <a title="Shoti" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/53373701-shoti"><img alt="Shoti" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1477072777p2/53373701.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2711286642?book_show_action=true">Feb 11, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Shoti" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Shoti" href="/user/show/53373701-shoti">Shoti</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/53373701-shoti?shelf=politics">politics</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/53373701-shoti?shelf=dystopia">dystopia</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2711286642" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer9665101026817943494">Jang Jin-sung was not just an ordinary poet. He was a court poet to Kim Jong-il, the despotic dictator, euphemistically ‘Dear Leader’, who ruled North Korea until his death in 2011. Jang was a young superstar when at the age of 28 he could so thoroughly impress Kim Jong-il with a poem that he gained the highest personal acknowledgment one could ever dream of in North Korea: he became one of Kim Jong-il&apos;s ‘Admitted’. The Admitted were held in such high esteem that even the dreadful Ministry of St</span>
  <span id="freeText9665101026817943494" style="display:none">Jang Jin-sung was not just an ordinary poet. He was a court poet to Kim Jong-il, the despotic dictator, euphemistically ‘Dear Leader’, who ruled North Korea until his death in 2011. Jang was a young superstar when at the age of 28 he could so thoroughly impress Kim Jong-il with a poem that he gained the highest personal acknowledgment one could ever dream of in North Korea: he became one of Kim Jong-il's ‘Admitted’. The Admitted were held in such high esteem that even the dreadful Ministry of State Security, the North Korean equivalent of Nazi Gestapo or Russian KGB, needed prior approval from Kim Jong-il to investigate or prosecute in their case. Jang enjoyed a pampered life by North Korean standards manifested in a steady flow of copious weekly food rations. Therefore, he was utterly shocked when he was allowed to leave Pyongyang for a short visit to his long unseen hometown in the countryside and found it being plagued by a devastating famine. Jang started to lose loyalty and become skeptical of the infallibility and righteousness of Dear Leader. After committing a seemingly banal error he had to flee the country to save his life.<br /><br />The escape of Jang and his friend from the North Korean and Chinese military / police / secret agents, their miserable suffering and desperate struggle to reach freedom are as gripping as any exciting thriller. What I found most unique though are the insights and perspectives Jang as a prominent defector could share about the hidden world of North Korea. <br /><br />Clearly, communist dictatorships can bloom and blossom in complete isolation only. As soon as they let their guard down and allow their populace to steal a glance at the incomparably higher living standards of the despised capitalist world there’s a danger that the accumulating inner steam shall burst apart their shaky system. Accordingly, obsession with isolation and thought control is deeply coded into the North Korean regime. Jang, like any other artists, had to compose works in response to specific requests from the Worker’s Party. Composing any work that was not assigned to the writer was interpreted by default as treason. The circulation of foreign books was limited to 100 copies distributed to the most reliable cadres. It’s chilling to see how North Korea manipulated the North Korean language itself. In order to consolidate the language and unify the private and public spheres of thought the Party’s Propaganda and Agitation Ministry set strict boundaries for the written and spoken words. When Jang found by chance a Korean translation of the Collected Works of Lord Byron he was shocked to see the unfamiliar ways in which the Korean language could be used. Before encountering Byron he did not know, for instance, that words such as ’Dear’, ’Great’ or ’Respected’ were adjectives for general use, not names inextricably belonging to the family name ’Kim’. That's the Orwellian Newspeak at its largest! <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/40961427.1984" title="1984 by George Orwell" rel="nofollow noopener">1984</a> was undoubtedly one of the foreign books translated into Korean and meticulously studied by Dear Leader and his cadres.<br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="9665101026817943494" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


