    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2233160597" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2233160597" />
    <a title="Ashley" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/5850153-ashley"><img alt="Ashley" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1583868889p2/5850153.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2233160597?book_show_action=true">Jan 13, 2018</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Ashley" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Ashley" href="/user/show/5850153-ashley">Ashley</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2233160597" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer360323209869891125">Probably the most compelling nonfiction account I&apos;ve read. I need time to put together my thoughts. This was intense and so so so so good.<br/><br/>This memoir read like a dystopian thriller. Details that we&apos;ve all seen in the Handmaid&apos;s Tale, the Hunger Games, Brave New World, 1984, the Giver. At times, the stories the author tells prove hard to digest. How can these things happen in the 1990s, the 2000s? These are tragic tales that belong in fiction. <br/><br/>The book is divided into three parts, each as page-tu</span>
  <span id="freeText360323209869891125" style="display:none">Probably the most compelling nonfiction account I've read. I need time to put together my thoughts. This was intense and so so so so good.<br /><br />This memoir read like a dystopian thriller. Details that we've all seen in the Handmaid's Tale, the Hunger Games, Brave New World, 1984, the Giver. At times, the stories the author tells prove hard to digest. How can these things happen in the 1990s, the 2000s? These are tragic tales that belong in fiction. <br /><br />The book is divided into three parts, each as page-turning as the others for different reasons. The first details his experience as a high-ranking cadre in the government, becoming one of the Admitted as a poet laureate. His experiences as a propaganda-spewing tool of the state feel familiar only from movies and books, or from the single party states of yore. But no, his rise happens in the 1990s. (This first part feels like some keen detailed world-building until you remember that it's not a novel. This is a real place full of real people.)Learning too many state secrets and the level at which his country shielded its people from the truths of the world leads to his disillusionment, which every encounter with his Dear Leader, trip to the countryside, and closed-door meeting only stoked. He and a friend, who also knew too much for his own good, decide to defect. <br /><br />And the second part begins, covering their heart-pounding escape. For thirty-five days the author runs, and for 100 pages I did not breathe. Every moment stressed me out and I had to keep turning the pages to find out how he made it to South Korea and how he could be alive telling his tale today. <br /><br />The third part gives us more backstory into North Korea's history and psyche that couldn't be included during the urgent pace of the other chapters. We learn about the author's post-escape life, and a high- level overview of the last decade or so. He is now a respected journalist living in South Korea running the website New Focus, a site dedicated to telling the world the truth about his home country. <br /><br />When I would share passages with my husband, facts that I'd learned, he'd look at me eyebrows cocked and ask, "Really? That sounds made up." Yes. Most of this is hard for an American living a life of comfort and privilege to believe. The lack of food and electricity. The strict rules for everything from job placement and acceptable language to haircuts and clothing. The violence, the censorship, the cultism of the ruling family. The complete and abject poverty of the majority of North Koreans, and the brainwashing that keeps them all under the state's thumb. It reads like fiction. Yet it confirms everything I've ever read about North Korea. It provides illuminating words to accompany the dismaying photos that journalists have dared to take. I was struck by the author's straight-forward storytelling method; it's no wonder that he was able to rise through the ranks as a writer. He can pull you in, yet he never resorts to impassioned dramatics or opinionated rants. He recounts EVERYTHING with about his traumas with objective matter-of-factness that only time could allow. <br /><br />This book hit me at so many levels. It should be read and studied by everyone. Not only eye-opening and educational, but humbling as well as entertaining (not like 'funny' but engaging and unputdownable). READ THIS BOOK. It's THAT good and even MORE important.</span>
  <a data-text-id="360323209869891125" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


