    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1007050736" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1007050736" />
    <a title="Doug Nordman" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/5772205-doug-nordman"><img alt="Doug Nordman" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1442599330p2/5772205.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1007050736?book_show_action=true">Jul 25, 2014</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Doug Nordman" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Doug Nordman" href="/user/show/5772205-doug-nordman">Doug Nordman</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="ebook 9781448177424" href="/book/show/20502208-dear-leader">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1007050736" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer7744303015433201524">I&apos;m retired from the U.S. Navy&apos;s submarine force, so I occasionally get questions about North Korea. Their isolation has led to years of speculation about their government and citizens. It&apos;s hard for experts to understand the country&apos;s culture and politics, let alone their economy or their military intentions. <br/><br/>&quot;Dear Leader&quot; is written by one of the most informed defectors to leave the country in years. Jang Jin-sung came to the attention of the leadership during college with his poetry and writi</span>
  <span id="freeText7744303015433201524" style="display:none">I'm retired from the U.S. Navy's submarine force, so I occasionally get questions about North Korea. Their isolation has led to years of speculation about their government and citizens. It's hard for experts to understand the country's culture and politics, let alone their economy or their military intentions. <br /><br />"Dear Leader" is written by one of the most informed defectors to leave the country in years. Jang Jin-sung came to the attention of the leadership during college with his poetry and writing, and it eventually led to a meeting with Kim himself. Jang was assigned to a department whose mission was studying South Korean culture and current events-- to help North Korea figure out how to "reunite" the two societies. In his job, Jang routinely consulted some of the most highly classified documents in North Korea: South Korean newspapers, magazines, and books.<br /><br />Jang loaned one of these forbidden publications to a friend, who accidentally lost it during his commute. Faced with prison, the two managed to escape Pyongyang for the northern border with China. They crossed the river and then faced weeks of winter survival as they evaded manhunts by the Chinese police. Ironically their elevated status in Pyongyang left them relatively well-fed and healthy, so they were not as emaciated as most North Korean defectors and were able to blend in with Chinese sympathizers. Eventually Jang found his way to a South Korean intelligence agent and was smuggled from China to South Korea. <br /><br />This is the most revealing look inside North Korea in at least a decade. Jang's escape story alternates with his memoirs of his family, friends, and government co-workers. He explains how the Kim family runs the country and how the generational succession really happened. He lays out the government structure and which branches have the real power. He describes how the economy works (or not) and how the citizens are taught to sacrifice their lives for the country (and its leader). He shows how most of what we know about North Korea is wrong, and how it's changing. <br /><br />The drama drags on at times, but most of the problems are caused by the defectors not understanding how to survive in the "free" society of China. They're victimized by their culture and they struggle to learn how to blend in and obtain funds to get to a South Korean embassy.<br /><br />You know the story ends well, but (spoiler) there are sacrifices. <br /><br />If you've ever wondered why it's so difficult to negotiate with North Korea, read this book. I sure hope it's appreciated by strategic thinkers in South Korea, China, and America. </span>
  <a data-text-id="7744303015433201524" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


