    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2433722142" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2433722142" />
    <a title="Bahram Zaeri" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/54313655-bahram-zaeri"><img alt="Bahram Zaeri" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1459062742p2/54313655.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2433722142?book_show_action=true">Aug 14, 2018</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Bahram Zaeri" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Bahram Zaeri" href="/user/show/54313655-bahram-zaeri">Bahram Zaeri</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Kindle Edition " href="/book/show/22034850-dear-leader">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2433722142" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer1116361438519794432">Beyond the myths and gossips about North Korea, this book gives a much more realistic view about what’s been happening in N.Korea since the foundation of the Kim dynasty. However, it’s more focused on the era of the second leader, Kim Jung-il, titled Dear Leader. The narrator is a North Korean poet (in fact a psychological warfare expertise) working for UFD (United Front Department) which works as the central machine of propaganda for N.K government. Employees of UFD have to produce literary and</span>
  <span id="freeText1116361438519794432" style="display:none">Beyond the myths and gossips about North Korea, this book gives a much more realistic view about what’s been happening in N.Korea since the foundation of the Kim dynasty. However, it’s more focused on the era of the second leader, Kim Jung-il, titled Dear Leader. The narrator is a North Korean poet (in fact a psychological warfare expertise) working for UFD (United Front Department) which works as the central machine of propaganda for N.K government. Employees of UFD have to produce literary and intellectual materials (books, magazines, poem, etc.) with fake identities of South Korean writers who praise Dear Leader and his way of governing the country. The book is the escape story of this agent to China and then South Korea. But remember a spy is still a spy no matter where they live. So, I can’t trust all the words in the book. I think the most important target of such books is the western audience. They have to believe that they are living in the heaven of absolute freedom. The softest way of doing this is to advertise the western values through the stories of the countries who don’t believe in the western interpretation of freedom.<br />All we hear in mass media is about a murderous regime ruling North Korea. But there’s something wrong here. They never talk about why North Korea decided to stay against the west, especially U.S. I think we should look for the reason in the imperialistic behavior of the U.S against the countries with different cultures and values. In fact, you have two ways: be a small part of U.S industries and their consumer, or never exist!. But the more important reason is the North Korea's neighbors and how they treat North Korea. As the book says, the biggest enemy of N.K is not the US, but China while they share the values of communism. Read this precious book to know about such conflicts and paradoxes. <br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="1116361438519794432" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


